<body>
<p>The bi-annual meeting GEOMED was held in October 2011 in Victoria, British Columbia, Canada. This meeting has as a focus development in methodology and applications in the area of disease mapping and risk assessment for public health. This meeting was also unusual in that it had an added focus on image analysis, and so also emphasized spatial biostatistical aspects not directed to population level public health. The meeting saw a variety of presentations in specific topic areas and as a result a range of papers have been developed. This special issue represents a selection of the papers with an emphasis on statistical methodology. As will be clear, a range of topics are represented here. These include: the use of a log Gaussian Cox Process with aggregate count data, Bayesian modeling of case event data, parasitic risk profiling, low birth weight models with latent space-time structure, focused test statistics, spatio-temporal P-spline models, and AFT survival models with mixture errors. A final word of thanks for all the hard work of the reviewers and editors upon which this issue is based.</p>
